title: For Sale:  Ruger Mini-14
postcontent:
Has one-piece pistol grip stock. The rail system is UTG and is one-piece that comes off easily and is made for a mini, as itslides rigth over the front of the barrel/stock.

The serial numbers start with 186-630xxx indicating that this is the model run from 1991-1999 I believe and this gun was made in 97/98.

Take off the stock and the true "mini" is in incredible shape. The last two pics show the internal front and back of the chamber and I couldn't get my camera to take a decent pic of the inside of the barrel but it is bright, shiny and the rifling is great. The gun shoots perfectly. The action is smooth and crisp. The magazine go in tight and crisp and snaps right into place, where I've had other minis that you fought with the darn thing to get it in there.

The barrel and top of the gun are very very clean and the only blemishes on the thing are a couple nicks on the suppressor and the stock has use marks.

This would be a perfect gun to throw an optic on and use as it is or to take off the stock and rails, sell them, and build whatever you want. I'd put a tactical folding stock on it from tapco or some other brand and just use a regular scope mount with a 3-9x30 myself. Or one could just put a nice red dot on the upper rail of this setup and go.

Anyhow, I hope this better explains the gun. I wish I had the original stock for it, but I don't. The nice thing about these mini's is that there are hundreds of cheap things that can be done to customize them on ebay, amazon and all over. Or if someone wanted a cheap really light mini, take off the rails in about 5 minutes and use the peep sights and go spray some lead at the coyotes.

$500 and thanks for looking. 

Any questions or more pics, call/text (515) 6six4-5nine78. Thanks.

I have a LaRue Tactical SPR / M4 Scope Mount QD LT104 that I have sitting around in the safe I am asking 200 obo  

The Industry Standard.
 The LT104 is the best mount made for attaching high-power riflescopes onto flattop-style AR15's, period.

 The LT104 places the centerline of the optic 1.5" above the top of the rail for optimum cheek weld with a variety of AR-platform rifles. The cantilever positions the scope out front over the handguard, eliminating the need to span from the receiver to the handguard. The cantilever also allows the shooter to obtain proper eye relief.

 The popularity of the SPR series of mounts is partially due to the innovative backbone that connects the split vertical rings. This design provides a more robust platform for the optics, increases repeatability, and eliminates the need for time-consuming lapping. The rings are precision-machined with the tightest tolerances, and feature threaded steel inserts, built to withstand a lifetime of abuse.

 Like all LaRue mounts, it is precision-machined out of bar-stock aluminum and anodized. The locking LaRue Speed Levers provide outstanding return to zero; the optic can be removed, and replaced, without loss of zero. Guaranteed.

 Assembly and adjustment only takes a few minutes, then off to the range.

title: For Sale:  WINCHESTER MODEL 12 ***Pristine Condition*** PRE-64-12 GAUGE**ATTN COLLECTORS**
postcontent:
Up for sale is the very Famous Winchester Model 12 its a Pre-64 and heres a little about the Model 12 before i get into detail and tell you more about the awesome example i have:

The famous Winchester Model 1912 pump shotgun was designed by Winchester's Thomas C. Johnson. Introduced in 20 gauge in 1912, 16 and 12 gauge guns followed in 1914. From its debut until the end of the 1950's, the Winchester Model 1912 was the pump shotgun, long known as "the perfect repeater." After 1919, the model designation was shortened to "Model 12," but the gun remained the same. Oh, sure, Ithaca, Stevens and Remington guns had their fans, but it was Winchester's Model 12 that dominated both the market and the public consciousness for decades. However, by the beginning of the 1960's, the times were a changin', to paraphrase Bob Dylan.

title: For Sale:  S&W 38/44 Heavy Duty 1934
postcontent:
The S&W 38/44 was the predecessor to the .357 magnum. In the late 1920s Police wanted more power in a handgun. S&W chambered their large N-frame revolver in .38 Special and Remington developed a high velocity .38 Special cartridge firing a 158gr LRN bullet at 1180 fps. The ammunition was known by several names: .38 Hi-Speed, .38 High Velocity, .38 Super Police depending on who made it. In 1935 the case was slightly lengthen and the .357 Magnum was born. These large frame revolvers are a pleasure to shoot with standard .38 Special ammunition and the S&W .38/44 HD was a popular seller right up until it was discontinued as the Model 20 in 1966.
This is a nice example of the Pre-War Heavy Duty Made in 1934. The bore and chambers are excellent and as well as timing and lock up. The gun was refinished at some point and the new finish does show some wear from normal use. The stocks are not original and are of later manufacture. If not for the refinish and stocks, this gun would be worth twice what I'm asking. 
This gun has NOT been altered to chamber .357 magnum ammunition.
Its still an excellent example of an early Heavy Duty and a fine shooter.

For sale to TN Residents only. FTF You will be required to provide Driver's License info for my records.

title: For Sale:  1840 U.S. Johnston Middconn flintlock pistol
postcontent: This exceptional example of a .54 caliber, smoothbore, flintlock pistol is one of approximately 18,000 Model 1836 pistols manufactured by Robert Johnson of Middletown, Connecticut between 1836 and 1844. (This particular example in 1840). The Model 1836 was widely considered to be the best designed and manufactured flintlock pistol. The pistol has an 8 1/2 inch round barrel with a brass front sight blade, swivel ramrod with button head and iron mountings. The barrel, ramrod, buttcap, barrel band and trigger guard are "bright". The lock plate, hammer, and tang were casehardened. The lock is marked "U.S. / R.JOHNSON / MIDDN CONN / 1840" below the brass pan. The left rear of the barrel is marked "US / JH / P" and the left flat is marked with the letter "P". The Model 1836 Flintlock Pistol was the standard issue handgun of the Mexican War. It's use continued, converted to percussion, during the Civil War.
